{{Infobox Cave | name = Yerphal Caves | photo =Yerphale stupa.jpg | photo_caption =Remains of a stupa in Yerphal caves. | location = | depth = | length = | map = India#India Maharashtra |relief=yes | map_width = | map_caption = | label = Yerphal Caves | map_alt = | coords = {{coord|17.382077|73.942973|display=inline, title|region:IN_type:landmark}} | survey = | survey_format = | discovery = | geology = | entrance_count = | entrance_list = | difficulty = | hazards = | access = | translation = | language = | pronunciation = }} '''Yerphal Caves''', also '''Yerphale Caves''', are a small group of Buddhist caves located near Umbraj, [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]. The caves were only discovered recently, in 1979.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Qureshi |first1=Dulari |title=The Rock-cut Temples of Western India |date=2010 |publisher=Bharatiya Kala Prakashan |isbn=9788180902024 |page=346 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7GVEAQAAIAAJ |language=en}}</ref> It is located not far from the [[Karad Caves]] (about 25&nbsp;km).
The group contains a small [[chaitya]] hall with an [[apsidal]] plan with a [[stupa]] inside.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rujivacharakul |first1=Vimalin |last2=Hahn |first2=H. Hazel |last3=Oshima |first3=Ken Tadashi |last4=Christensen |first4=Peter |title=Architecturalized Asia: Mapping a Continent through History |date=2013 |publisher=Hong Kong University Press |isbn=9789888208050 |page=141 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FCoWAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA141 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=MA/> There are also two cells, and an unfinished cave. The caves can be dated to the first half of the 2nd century CE.<ref name=MA>{{cite web |title=Yerphal monastery, (towards) Umbraj, Maharashtra, IN - Mapping Buddhist Monasteries |url=http://monastic-asia.wikidot.com/yerphal |website=monastic-asia.wikidot.com |language=en}}</ref>
